==English==
===Etymology===
Latin [[paronomasia#Larin|paronomasia]], from the Greek [[παρα-]] + [[ονομασια]] ‘naming’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /pærənə'meɪzɪə/

===Noun===
'''paronomasia'''
# a [[pun]] or play on words
#:*'''1984''': he gloomily regarded his new digital watch, faintly fascinated by the onward march of the square figures which turned one into the other with insolent ease, a kind of numerical '''paronomasia'''. — Anthony Burgess, ''Enderby's Dark Lady''
#:*'''1997''': Ev’rywhere but at Norfolk, where talk of Passion far outweighs its Enactment,– indeed, the Sailors’ '''Paronomasia''' for that wretched Place, is ‘No-Fuck’. — Thomas Pynchon, ''Mason & Dixon''